1 (b) “Cultural and linguistic competency” means cultural and linguistic abilities
2 that can be incorporated into therapeutic and medical evaluation and treatment, including:
3 (1) Direct communication in the patient’s primary language;
4 (2) Understanding and applying the roles that culture, ethnicity, and race
5 play in diagnosis, treatment, and clinical care; and
6 (3) Awareness of how the attitudes, values, and beliefs of health care
7 providers and patients influence and impact professional and patient relations.
8 (c) “Health care professional” includes a physician, nurse, dentist, social worker,
9 psychologist, pharmacist, health educator, or other allied health professional.
10 (d) “Implicit bias” means a bias in judgment that results from subtle cognitive
11 processes, including the following prejudices and stereotypes that often operate at a level
12 below conscious awareness and without intentional control:
13 (1) Prejudicial negative feelings or beliefs about a group that an individual
14 holds without being aware of the feelings or beliefs; and
15 (2) Unconscious attributions of particular qualities to a member of a
16 specific social group that are influenced by experience and based on learned associations
17 between various qualities and social categories, including race and gender.
18 (e) “Program” means the Cultural and Linguistic Health Care Professional
19 Competency Program.
20 (F) “STRUCTURAL RACISM” MEANS A SYSTEM OF INHERITED
21 INSTITUTIONAL SETTINGS THAT PROVIDE DIFFERENTIAL OPPORTUNITIES FOR
22 HEALTH CARE, EDUCATION, HOUSING, EMPLOYMENT, AND THE ENVIRONMENT TO
23 AN INDIVIDUAL BASED ON THE INDIVIDUAL’S RACE.
24 20–1302.
25 (a) There is a Cultural and Linguistic Health Care Professional Competency
26 Program.
27 (b) The purpose of the Program is to:
28 (1) Provide for a voluntary program in which educational classes are
29 offered to health care professionals to teach health care professionals:
30 (i) Methods to improve the health care professionals’ cultural and
31 linguistic competency to communicate with non–English speaking patients and patients
32 from other cultures who are English speaking;

